  {"title":"SAMHSA — Program Description: Co-Occurring Disorders Treatment","funder_name":"SAMHSA","funder_type":"federal","program_name":"Grants for the Benefit of Homeless Individuals","cfda_number":"93.914","section_key":"program_description","section_title":"Program Description","org_types":["nonprofit"],"program_types":["health","mental_health","substance_use","homelessness"],"tags":["SAMHSA","co-occurring","mental_health","homeless"],"win_count":7,"use_count":19,"typical_word_limit":1000,"content_md":"[Organization]'s proposed Integrated Recovery Program (IRP) will deliver evidence-based treatment for co-occurring substance use and mental health disorders to homeless and unstably housed individuals in [Service Area].\n\n**Theoretical Framework:** IRP uses the SAMHSA-endorsed Integrated Dual Diagnosis Treatment (IDDT) model, which treats substance use and mental health disorders simultaneously rather than sequentially, reducing the 'door-to-door' barrier that causes treatment dropout.\n\n**Services Delivered:**\n\n*Assertive Outreach:* Two full-time Outreach Specialists will conduct daily engagement at encampments, shelters, and emergency departments. Goal: 120 individuals engaged per year.\n\n*Comprehensive Assessment:* Licensed Clinical Social Workers administer AUDIT-C, PHQ-9, DAST-10, and ACE screening tools within 72 hours of engagement. Individual treatment plans developed within 5 business days.\n\n*Integrated Treatment:* MAT (buprenorphine, naltrexone) provided by an on-site prescribing physician (0.5 FTE). Individual and group therapy delivered by Licensed Professional Counselors using Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) and Motivational Enhancement Therapy (MET).\n\n*Housing Navigation:* Dedicated Housing Navigator coordinates with CoC continuum to secure permanent supportive housing placements. Target: 60% of enrolled clients housed within 6 months.\n\n*Peer Support:* Four Peer Recovery Specialists (Certified Recovery Coaches) with lived experience provide recovery coaching, medication adherence support, and crisis de-escalation."},

